               <p>SECOND COUNT, for uttering the same.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-203-person1695">
                  THOMAS 
                  ALLAN
               <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1695" type="surname" value="ALLAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1695" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1695" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18320906-203-viclabel1141" type="occupation">warehouseman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-203-victim1694 t18320906-203-viclabel1141"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18320906-203-crimeloc1142">Friday-street, Cheapside</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-203-crimeloc1142" type="placeName" value="Friday-street, Cheapside"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-203-crimeloc1142" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-203-off1140 t18320906-203-crimeloc1142"></join>, and have a partner; the prisoner was our <rs id="t18320906-203-deflabel1143" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-203-defend1692 t18320906-203-deflabel1143"></join>; he carried goods to different wharfs and booking-offices. On the 16th of July our packer gave him a box to carry to the wharf - On the <rs id="t18320906-203-cd1144" type="crimeDate">23rd of July</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-203-off1140 t18320906-203-cd1144"></join> he produced to me two receipts for 1s. 6d. each, for wharfage and shipping charges; here is one signed "Beloe;" I paid him 1s. 6d. for that - I suspected it at the time.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. How long was he in your employ? A. About six weeks as porter; he gave me notice to quit on the Monday morning after I kept the note back - our porters occasionally employ journeymen carters as they pass along to take goods to the wharfs, but not by our order - that is the cheapest way, but I never saw him employ them; I believe our porters have done so, by their charging it in their books - they sometimes have a heavy load, and give a man 3d. or 6d. to assist if he is going their way; they frequently charge me for "a pitch;" they have no authority from me to employ chance carters - when I have found they had got a cart to assist, when they did not want it, I have objected to their charge, and they have said the load was too heavy.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-203-person1696">
                  DANIEL 
                  BELOE
               <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1696" type="surname" value="BELOE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1696" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1696" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to Mr. Wilson, of Smith's wharf, Tooley-street. Part of this receipt is in my writing; I wrote it for 1s., it has been altered to 1s. 6d. - I am positive it was only for 1s. when I signed it; the 6d. is not in my writing.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. How many of these do you sign in a day? A. I may sign fifty - I enter them in a book, which I have here; I cannot say whether the prisoner is the person who paid me 1s.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-203-person1697">
                  JOSEPH 
                  RENSHAW
               <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1697" type="surname" value="RENSHAW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1697" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-203-person1697" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I received the prisoner in charge.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was a perfect stranger to the trade, and got a carter to take the goods to the wharf - I stood by the cart; they got the receipts from the wharf, and gave them to me as they are - if they were altered, it was before they came into my hands.</p>


